Title¶

"Unveiling Topics in Amazon Reviews and BBC News: A Topic Modeling Approach"

Summary¶

This project explores the fascinating realm of topic modeling using natural language processing (NLP) techniques. By analyzing a dataset containing Amazon reviews, the main aim to uncover underlying themes and topics within the text data. Leveraging the power of topic modeling algorithms, I will dive into the content and structure of the reviews and news articles to identify key topics and their prevalence. Through a step-by-step process, preprocessing of the text, apply topic modeling algorithms, and visualize the results. The insights gained from this analysis provide valuable knowledge about the most significant topics in the data, shedding light on the consumer sentiments expressed in Amazon reviews. This project offers a comprehensive exploration of topic modeling techniques and their practical application to real-world textual data.

Business Problem

In the rapidly evolving e-commerce landscape, understanding customer sentiment and feedback is crucial for businesses to improve their products and services. Amazon, being a global leader in e-commerce, receives millions of product reviews from customers worldwide. These reviews are a rich source of customer insights but manually analyzing such a vast amount of text data is time-consuming and practically infeasible.

The challenge is to develop an automated system that can process these reviews, identify key topics that customers are talking about, and extract named entities such as product names, organizations, locations, etc. This will help Amazon or any agency to quickly identify common customer complaints, popular products, and other valuable insights that can inform business strategy.

Preprocessing¶

For this there is a algorithm which I am going to build, which involves

  • Tokenize each review (using gensim)
  • Remove stop words (including punctuations)
  • Lemmatize (using spacy)

Lemmatization is an crutial step and its highly recommended because when building topic models,Without lemmatization, there is a risk of generating topics that contain similar words, such as "Cream" and "Creams," which essentially refer to the same concept.

# Function to convert sentences to words
def sent_to_words(sentences, deacc=True):  # deacc=True removes punctuations
    for sentence in sentences:
        yield(simple_preprocess(str(sentence), deacc=deacc))

In this case, stopwords.words('english') returns a list of stopwords specific to the English language. Stopwords are commonly occurring words that are often removed from text data during natural language processing tasks because they do not carry significant meaning and can be considered noise in the analysis.

Further analysis

I am going to preprocess and filter the data further, These preprocessing steps help remove stopwords and perform lemmatization to transform the text data into a cleaner and more meaningful representation,

In [27]:
import spacy
from gensim.utils import simple_preprocess
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

# Defining a list of stopwords
stopword_list = set(stopwords.words('english'))

# Defining functions for stopwords, bigrams, trigrams and lemmatization
def eliminate_stopwords(texts):
    return [[word for word in simple_preprocess(str(document)) if word not in stopword_list] for document in texts]

def perform_lemmatization(texts, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV']):
    output_texts = []
    for text in texts:
        doc = nlp(' '.join(text))
        output_texts.append([token.lemma_ for token in doc if token.pos_ in allowed_postags])
    return output_texts

# Removing Stop Words
data_words_no_stops = eliminate_stopwords(data_words)

# Initialize spacy 'en_core_web_sm' model, keeping only tagger component (for efficiency)
nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm', disable=['parser', 'ner'])

#  lemmatization keeping only noun, adj, vb, adv
data_lemmatized = perform_lemmatization(data_words_no_stops, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV'])

# Print the third document after lemmatization
print(data_lemmatized[3])

Hyper parameter tuning¶

Now creating a function "compute_coherence_values_tuning" for tuning the LDA model by evaluating different combinations of the number of topics and alpha values which includes various Parameters, like

  • dictionary
  • corpus
  • texts
  • num_topics_range
  • alpha_range
In [35]:
def compute_coherence_values_tuning(dictionary, corpus, texts, num_topics_range, alpha_range):
    coherence_values_tuning = []
    model_list_tuning = []
    for num_topics in num_topics_range:
        for alpha in alpha_range:
            model_tuning = gensim.models.LdaMulticore(corpus=corpus, num_topics=num_topics, id2word=dictionary, alpha=alpha)
            model_list_tuning.append(model_tuning)
            coherencemodel_tuning = CoherenceModel(model=model_tuning, texts=texts, dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
            coherence_values_tuning.append({'num_topics': num_topics, 'alpha': alpha, 'coherence': coherencemodel_tuning.get_coherence()})

    return model_list_tuning, coherence_values_tuning

# Defining the function to plot coherence values
def plot_coherence(coherence_df, alpha_range, num_topics_range):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,6))

    for i, alpha in enumerate(alpha_range):
        plt.subplot(1, len(alpha_range), i+1)
        alpha_subset = coherence_df[coherence_df['alpha'] == alpha]
        plt.plot(alpha_subset['num_topics'], alpha_subset['coherence'])
        plt.xlabel('Num Topics')
        plt.ylabel('Coherence Value')
        plt.title('Alpha = {0}'.format(alpha))
        plt.ylim([0.30, 1])
        plt.legend('Coherence Value', loc='upper left')
        plt.xticks(num_topics_range)

# Plotting  the coherence values
plot_coherence(coherence_df_tuning, alpha_range, num_topics_range)

Now another Method to do is called NER, Name entity Recognition

  • Named Entity Recognition (NER) is a process where an algorithm takes a string of text (sentence or paragraph) as input and identifies relevant nouns (people, places, and organizations) that are mentioned in that string.
  • ORG (Organizations)
  • PERSON (Persons)
  • GPE (Geo-Political Entity)
  • DATES/TIME
  • MONEY

import spacy
from spacy import displacy
from collections import Counter
import en_core_web_sm
nlp = en_core_web_sm.load()

# Function to extract Named Entities
def extract_named_entities(text):
    doc = nlp(text)
    return [(X.text, X.label_) for X in doc.ents]

# Appling the function to the 'headline_text' column

(early Feb..., DATE): It identifies the phrase "early Feb..." as a date (DATE).

Conclusion¶

In this project,

  • I performed an extensive analysis of Amazon reviews using various Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques.
  • I started with data cleaning and preprocessing, where we removed unnecessary characters, performed tokenization, and lemmatization. This step was crucial to convert the raw reviews into a format that could be easily analyzed.
  • I used the Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) model from the Gensim library to perform topic modeling. This helped us identify the main topics that customers were discussing in their reviews.
  • I visualized the topics and their keywords using PyLDAvis, which provided an intuitive way to understand the model's output.
  • I performed hyperparameter tuning on the LDA model to find the optimal number of topics and the best value for the alpha parameter
  • I used coherence score as a metric to evaluate the quality of the topics generated by the model. The optimal model had a coherence score of 0.44
  • After topic modeling, I performed Named Entity Recognition (NER) using the Spacy library. This allowed us to extract important entities such as product names, brands, and locations from the reviews.
  • Hence, Understanding the main topics of discussion in the reviews can help identify common customer complaints, popular features, and areas for improvement.
